500
00:26:48,862 --> 00:26:49,662
Check this out.

501
00:26:49,662 --> 00:26:53,164
So we have art cutouts, and we send these

502
00:26:53,164 --> 00:26:53,904
to our content creators.

503
00:26:53,904 --> 00:26:57,326
And this is useful for even bloggers, too.

504
00:26:57,326 --> 00:26:59,547
Anyone that makes any content for your game,

505
00:26:59,547 --> 00:27:02,568
they have high quality assets.

506
00:27:02,568 --> 00:27:04,509
So if I click this, it's going to be

507
00:27:04,509 --> 00:27:06,970
a giant, high resolution image, which is probably

508
00:27:06,970 --> 00:27:07,930
going to take forever to load.

509
00:27:08,405 --> 00:27:09,125
And so it's huge.

510
00:27:09,125 --> 00:27:11,127
You can't see it, but it's transparent.

511
00:27:11,127 --> 00:27:14,290
So they can use it on whatever article, or if they're

512
00:27:14,290 --> 00:27:16,391
making, you know, YouTube, they have the thumbnails.

513
00:27:16,391 --> 00:27:19,514
They can make it effortlessly, over and over.

514
00:27:19,514 --> 00:27:27,320
And that encourages them to play your game.

515
00:27:27,320 --> 00:27:30,663
So a lot of people need support for their game.

516
00:27:30,663 --> 00:27:34,266
And for that, you can use Freshdesk.

517
00:27:34,266 --> 00:27:35,887
Freshdesk is a.

518
00:27:36,808 --> 00:27:39,931
support desk service, and it's free.

519
00:27:39,931 --> 00:27:44,314
And what's special about them is that you can have a support email,

520
00:27:44,314 --> 00:27:46,456
like support at imperium42.com,

521
00:27:46,456 --> 00:27:51,000
and the email will turn into a ticket automatically.

522
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:56,584
So that's really easy, so you can get your whole team to collaborate with each other.

523
00:27:56,584 --> 00:27:59,786
And you can have, there's also private notes and automated things,

524
00:27:59,786 --> 00:28:03,369
like if you have a scammer emailing you saying,

525
00:28:03,369 --> 00:28:05,531
please give me 20 keys, then you can...

526
00:28:05,881 --> 00:28:10,063
you can have an automated response based on certain keywords and stuff.

527
00:28:10,063 --> 00:28:13,924
So there's always communication going with tickets.

528
00:28:13,924 --> 00:28:16,946
So everyone knows what's happening at the same time.

529
00:28:16,946 --> 00:28:19,246
So let's say you're busy, you say,

530
00:28:19,246 --> 00:28:21,327
Elsa, please look at this ticket.

531
00:28:21,327 --> 00:28:24,549
Then she'll go and she'll already know what's going on.

532
00:28:24,549 --> 00:28:31,251
There's no information ever lost between the agents looking at the support tickets.

533
00:28:31,251 --> 00:28:33,012
Buffer is amazing.

534
00:28:34,065 --> 00:28:40,930
will queue up your post for social media and send it to all the social media platforms

535
00:28:40,930 --> 00:28:42,571
at the same time.

536
00:28:42,571 --> 00:28:45,273
So let's say you have, it's a pain, right?

537
00:28:45,273 --> 00:28:51,918
You're doing Twitch, Facebook, Instagram, I think they have others too even, like Pinterest,

538
00:28:51,918 --> 00:28:54,539
all the other little ones no one cares that much about.

539
00:28:54,539 --> 00:29:00,924
But you can have them, and you queue up your post and it'll send it at the times that Buffer

540
00:29:00,924 --> 00:29:02,265
thinks is the perfect time.

541
00:29:02,690 --> 00:29:04,931
for you to send them. It'll automatically space it out for you.

542
00:29:04,931 --> 00:29:12,597
So let's say, in our case, the best time to send it out is 2am because we target America.

543
00:29:12,597 --> 00:29:17,121
And so, if we go like, 2am, I'm not going to stay up until 2am and post it.

544
00:29:17,121 --> 00:29:19,983
But, I can queue it up to buffer, and I can queue it up many times.

545
00:29:19,983 --> 00:29:22,525
I can queue up maybe 10 posts at a time.

546
00:29:22,525 --> 00:29:27,829
So I queue up 10 at a time, and it'll send it out to Twitter, Instagram, Facebook,

547
00:29:27,829 --> 00:29:29,450
all at 2am automatically.

548
00:29:29,989 --> 00:29:31,190
So this is good stuff.

549
00:29:31,190 --> 00:29:37,514
And if you add multiple, it will automatically space it out.

550
00:29:37,514 --> 00:29:40,496
Buffer.com. It's free, too.

551
00:29:40,496 --> 00:29:43,858
I'm not going to talk much about ads, but if you do do ads,

552
00:29:43,858 --> 00:29:50,622
in our experience, the best thing to look out for is don't do pay-per-view.

553
00:29:50,622 --> 00:29:52,864
That's just... that's meant for companies like Coke, Coca-Cola,

554
00:29:52,864 --> 00:29:55,926
that want brand recognition.

555
00:29:55,926 --> 00:29:57,787
But you don't want brand recognition.

556
00:29:57,787 --> 00:29:59,808
I mean, it's nice, but you want conversion.

557
00:30:00,293 --> 00:30:03,595
You want people to click on your ad and buy the game.

558
00:30:03,595 --> 00:30:07,117
I mean, if they know it but don't buy it,

559
00:30:07,117 --> 00:30:09,038
it shouldn't matter to most of you.

560
00:30:09,038 --> 00:30:09,659
So pay per click.

561
00:30:09,659 --> 00:30:11,460
You can track this stuff.

562
00:30:11,460 --> 00:30:13,141
You can track most of the conversions.

563
00:30:13,141 --> 00:30:15,662
Although, if you use Steam, it's sort of hard

564
00:30:15,662 --> 00:30:16,723
to see if it works or not.

565
00:30:16,723 --> 00:30:19,104
So I still don't recommend it that much.

566
00:30:19,104 --> 00:30:20,925
But if you do it, do that.

567
00:30:20,925 --> 00:30:24,107
GIFs and videos work the best for these types

568
00:30:24,107 --> 00:30:26,788
when we're looking at engagements.

569
00:30:33,881 --> 00:30:35,441
So what have I learned?

570
00:30:35,441 --> 00:30:37,782
Read the fine print.

571
00:30:37,782 --> 00:30:40,743
Now, when you launch that online game,

572
00:30:40,743 --> 00:30:42,503
you launch World of Warcraft or something,

573
00:30:42,503 --> 00:30:44,664
and you see the big terms of service,

574
00:30:44,664 --> 00:30:47,545
I know everyone just skips past that.

575
00:30:47,545 --> 00:30:53,566
But now you're in management, so you need to read this stuff.

576
00:30:53,566 --> 00:30:59,928
So for example, we were choosing between our back end of service.

577
00:30:59,928 --> 00:31:03,309
And at the time, we chose PlayFab.

578
00:31:03,616 --> 00:31:05,217
for our very first one, before GameSparks.

579
00:31:05,217 --> 00:31:07,839
And before that, as we're working on that,

580
00:31:07,839 --> 00:31:10,722
I spent about a year of development

581
00:31:10,722 --> 00:31:12,143
adding them into the game.

582
00:31:12,143 --> 00:31:14,645
It was supposed to be $10 a month.

583
00:31:14,645 --> 00:31:16,947
And then when we launched, I got the contract.

584
00:31:16,947 --> 00:31:20,069
And so maybe about two weeks before we launched,

585
00:31:20,069 --> 00:31:21,110
I got the contract.

586
00:31:21,110 --> 00:31:21,991
I read it over.

587
00:31:21,991 --> 00:31:25,113
And suddenly, I realized I'm not paying $10 a month

588
00:31:25,113 --> 00:31:25,834
once I launch.

589
00:31:25,834 --> 00:31:29,137
I'm paying $300 a month once I first launch.

590
00:31:29,137 --> 00:31:31,238
And for a company with no budget.

591
00:31:31,831 --> 00:31:40,575
If you've launched with Steam before, you don't get paid for even two months.

592
00:31:40,575 --> 00:31:45,877
You have to wait two months and then you get paid.

593
00:31:45,877 --> 00:31:49,758
I want to explain FinePrint in Chinese.

594
00:31:49,758 --> 00:31:50,339
Sure.

595
00:31:50,339 --> 00:31:57,561
FinePrint is a document that you have to read carefully.

596
00:31:58,635 --> 00:32:01,216
Yeah, so we thought we were paying $10 a month.

597
00:32:01,216 --> 00:32:03,818
Now we're paying $300 a month, US dollars.

598
00:32:03,818 --> 00:32:06,820
So that's a big difference.

599
00:32:06,820 --> 00:32:08,822
And so we couldn't afford that.

600
00:32:08,822 --> 00:32:13,845
And so we ended up having to spend 150 hours to port

601
00:32:13,845 --> 00:32:15,686
to the competitor, GameSparks.

602
00:32:15,686 --> 00:32:17,928
And in the end, I did look ahead.

603
00:32:17,928 --> 00:32:22,791
And they said that they would give me a free account,

604
00:32:22,791 --> 00:32:24,472
since we were a very small team.

605
00:32:24,472 --> 00:32:26,493
And so you guys can do that, too.

606
00:32:26,867 --> 00:32:29,548
If you go to gamesparks.com and you have a small team,

607
00:32:29,548 --> 00:32:36,073
small as in full-time, you can get a free Gamesparks BaaS account.

608
00:32:36,073 --> 00:32:41,557
As long as you have under 100,000 people per month,

609
00:32:41,557 --> 00:32:44,499
which is a lot, we don't even have half that,

610
00:32:44,499 --> 00:32:49,182
then you get it for free, with no limitations.

611
00:32:49,182 --> 00:32:51,104
It's awesome.

612
00:32:54,511 --> 00:32:59,293
So as for PR firms, a lot of people, they wonder if they need PR or not.

613
00:32:59,293 --> 00:33:01,635
And the answer is probably no.

614
00:33:01,635 --> 00:33:03,095
Almost every time.

615
00:33:03,095 --> 00:33:09,238
The PR guys, what I just taught you earlier about Buffer and all that, they're using that.

616
00:33:09,238 --> 00:33:09,939
You can do that.

617
00:33:09,939 --> 00:33:14,161
It seems like they're doing a lot, but all they do is they know the tools.

618
00:33:14,161 --> 00:33:21,965
And we actually hired a PR firm at the beginning for our Kickstarter, and we spent about $1

619
00:33:22,447 --> 00:33:25,048
We spent too much. We spent like $2,000 US dollars,

620
00:33:25,048 --> 00:33:26,929
$3,000 US dollars, which was all of our budget on PR.

621
00:33:26,929 --> 00:33:29,150
And so this ended up being a mistake.

622
00:33:29,150 --> 00:33:38,256
So in the end, I realized that people, bloggers and news people for gaming,

623
00:33:38,256 --> 00:33:43,999
they don't really care about Kickstarters.

624
00:33:43,999 --> 00:33:50,083
You know, people have Kickstarters so often these days that it's just not news anymore.

625
00:33:50,786 --> 00:33:55,689
And so many Kickstarters don't actually come into real games.

626
00:33:55,689 --> 00:34:01,093
So people are afraid to cover you if you have a Kickstarter.

627
00:34:01,093 --> 00:34:07,757
It may be better if you're new, if you actually launched.

628
00:34:07,757 --> 00:34:12,480
But even then, you can actually Google for press release

629
00:34:12,480 --> 00:34:13,801
companies instead.

630
00:34:13,801 --> 00:34:16,823
And you pay maybe $45, maybe $50 US, and they

631
00:34:17,864 --> 00:34:23,766
will distribute out to maybe hundreds, thousands of emails and companies.

632
00:34:23,766 --> 00:34:26,167
You can do this yourself for $50 instead of $3,000.

633
00:34:26,167 --> 00:34:30,629
Because just what I told you, this is what they do.

634
00:34:30,629 --> 00:34:32,790
They know the tools, they know the sources.

635
00:34:32,790 --> 00:34:37,592
And if you know what to Google, you can do it for so much cheaper.

636
00:34:37,592 --> 00:34:39,273
So just skip PR firms.

637
00:34:39,273 --> 00:34:44,175
If you're going to do a PR firm anyway, at least go to their website.

638
00:34:44,175 --> 00:34:47,136
They'll always have client lists.

639
00:34:47,627 --> 00:34:50,829
then contact those developers directly.

640
00:34:50,829 --> 00:34:52,610
So somebody recently contacted me,

641
00:34:52,610 --> 00:34:53,731
because we're on their website still.

642
00:34:53,731 --> 00:34:55,532
They asked me, what do you think about these guys?

643
00:34:55,532 --> 00:34:58,714
We're about to spend a few thousand.

644
00:34:58,714 --> 00:35:01,836
And we didn't have very good things to say.

645
00:35:01,836 --> 00:35:07,980
And so we may have saved them some money.

646
00:35:07,980 --> 00:35:12,442
So you want to set your public milestones two weeks

647
00:35:12,442 --> 00:35:14,684
after you're ready.

648
00:35:14,684 --> 00:35:15,084
We made a mistake.

649
00:35:15,750 --> 00:35:22,094
So when we launched our Alpha for the first time, we launched on the same day we were ready.

650
00:35:22,094 --> 00:35:25,636
We said, we think we're going to be ready by this day?

651
00:35:25,636 --> 00:35:28,197
Well, we were, literally.

652
00:35:28,197 --> 00:35:32,220
So there was no buffer time in between.

653
00:35:32,220 --> 00:35:35,942
What ended up happening was we were in a rush, we couldn't sleep,

654
00:35:35,942 --> 00:35:41,565
we had to test a million miles an hour, we were stressed.

655
00:35:41,565 --> 00:35:43,326
It was a very stressful time.

656
00:35:44,197 --> 00:35:50,541
If we would have set our launch date maybe two weeks, or even a month after we're ready,

657
00:35:50,541 --> 00:35:54,324
we could polish it a little bit, we could take our time to test it.

658
00:35:54,324 --> 00:35:57,546
Lots of times there's always something small that,

659
00:35:57,546 --> 00:36:02,669
something small maybe takes five minutes to change, but may have a big impact.

660
00:36:02,669 --> 00:36:09,034
For example, let's say you have a tutorial and your tutorial button didn't work or something,

661
00:36:09,034 --> 00:36:13,657
then just an extra little bit of time after you think you're ready.

662
00:36:14,285 --> 00:36:18,607
it really makes a difference, not just for the players,

663
00:36:18,607 --> 00:36:20,247
but for your whole team and your body.

664
00:36:20,247 --> 00:36:22,208
We use Wikia for our documentation, our rules,

665
00:36:22,208 --> 00:36:26,890
our external localization.

666
00:36:26,890 --> 00:36:31,733
We don't have localization in the game yet.

667
00:36:31,733 --> 00:36:35,814
I know I'm surprised that you guys showed up,

668
00:36:35,814 --> 00:36:40,096
because we don't have Chinese localization yet.

669
00:36:40,096 --> 00:36:41,737
So thank you guys for coming.

