And then it grants this user gold in-game,

995
00:53:40,711 --> 00:53:42,292
even though I'm typing it from Discord.

996
00:53:42,292 --> 00:53:48,298
So you can think, oh, and also Discord just recently added rich presents.

997
00:53:48,854 --> 00:53:51,075
This is sort of like Steam, how they know what you're doing.

998
00:53:51,075 --> 00:53:56,438
Steam will say, he's playing Throne of Lies.

999
00:53:56,438 --> 00:53:58,619
And Discord goes even deeper.

1000
00:53:58,619 --> 00:54:02,941
Discord will say, he's playing Throne of Lies,

1001
00:54:02,941 --> 00:54:06,502
and he's on day two in game.

1002
00:54:06,502 --> 00:54:09,604
Or his game is just finishing, or something like that.

1003
00:54:09,604 --> 00:54:12,905
And sort of like Steam, there's even a Join button,

1004
00:54:12,905 --> 00:54:14,766
or a Spectate button you can use.

1005
00:54:14,766 --> 00:54:17,127
So there's a lot of stuff you can do.

1006
00:54:18,908 --> 00:54:22,550
people go crazy about titles and praise and stuff like recognition

1007
00:54:22,550 --> 00:54:26,312
because in our discord we have twelve thousand players

1008
00:54:26,312 --> 00:54:28,573
and it's really hard to stand out when there's

1009
00:54:28,573 --> 00:54:30,314
you know we have an average of

1010
00:54:30,314 --> 00:54:32,755
two thousand players online at the same time

1011
00:54:32,755 --> 00:54:33,756
so the list is just

1012
00:54:33,756 --> 00:54:35,777
it's just a dump of players

1013
00:54:35,777 --> 00:54:37,398
and so what ends up happening is

1014
00:54:37,398 --> 00:54:39,739
people want to stand out and so when they do

1015
00:54:39,739 --> 00:54:41,860
when they contribute to the wikia

1016
00:54:41,860 --> 00:54:43,100
or they report bugs

1017
00:54:43,100 --> 00:54:46,982
you can have a bugs section, a bugs channel, a feedback channel

1018
00:54:46,982 --> 00:54:47,543
if the

1019
00:54:48,449 --> 00:54:50,350
if they help new players a lot.

1020
00:54:50,350 --> 00:54:53,552
You can grant them titles to make them stand out.

1021
00:54:53,552 --> 00:54:55,314
And this really boosts morale, like crazy.

1022
00:54:55,314 --> 00:55:00,317
And for any of you that play online games,

1023
00:55:00,317 --> 00:55:02,438
if you attend like a GM event or something,

1024
00:55:02,438 --> 00:55:05,920
and you get an exclusive title, it's so cool, isn't it?

1025
00:55:05,920 --> 00:55:08,442
It's the same thing in Discord.

1026
00:55:08,442 --> 00:55:10,563
Players feel cool about it, and it

1027
00:55:10,563 --> 00:55:15,567
makes them want to engage even more in the community.

1028
00:55:15,567 --> 00:55:17,248
And what you can do, too, as game developers,

1029
00:55:17,585 --> 00:55:20,026
you can have an official game server.

1030
00:55:20,026 --> 00:55:24,388
So you can see our URL is actually discord.gg slash tol.

1031
00:55:24,388 --> 00:55:28,029
And so that's because we're an official game server.

1032
00:55:28,029 --> 00:55:29,270
It didn't take much to do it.

1033
00:55:29,270 --> 00:55:32,772
All we did is fill out an application and say, hey,

1034
00:55:32,772 --> 00:55:34,492
we're the real developers.

1035
00:55:34,492 --> 00:55:37,754
And this is the game that we're supporting.

1036
00:55:37,754 --> 00:55:42,056
And so suddenly you get an official verification.

1037
00:55:42,056 --> 00:55:43,997
You get the URL there.

1038
00:55:43,997 --> 00:55:45,717
And then when people join it, you

1039
00:55:45,717 --> 00:55:46,518
can actually get a

1040
00:55:48,112 --> 00:55:50,954
Let's see, discord.tv slash tol.

1041
00:55:50,954 --> 00:55:55,378
You can actually get some splash art, and it makes it look super cool.

1042
00:55:55,378 --> 00:55:56,319
It looks very official.

1043
00:55:56,319 --> 00:55:58,400
So, uh, oh, there it is.

1044
00:55:58,400 --> 00:56:01,523
So it looks sort of like this.

1045
00:56:01,523 --> 00:56:05,386
And you can customize the art in the background.

1046
00:56:05,386 --> 00:56:13,133
So, when you make your games, a lot of people are going to request game keys.

1047
00:56:13,133 --> 00:56:15,474
They're going to say, I'm press.

1048
00:56:15,474 --> 00:56:17,116
I'm a famous.

1049
00:56:19,582 --> 00:56:23,242
and they'll say, I have millions of views, trust me.

1050
00:56:23,242 --> 00:56:25,463
And they're going to ask for keys.

1051
00:56:25,463 --> 00:56:32,704
So, what you do is, you say, hey, come to Discord,

1052
00:56:32,704 --> 00:56:35,105
link your Twitch account, link your Twitter account,

1053
00:56:35,105 --> 00:56:40,126
or you can even, they can also support Steam, link your Steam account,

1054
00:56:40,126 --> 00:56:43,587
and we'll give you keys. You'll find very fast

1055
00:56:43,587 --> 00:56:48,648
that half the people never come to Discord because they're fake.

1056
00:56:49,453 --> 00:56:56,659
So, more than half, I'd say about 75% of the people that ask for keys are fake.

1057
00:56:56,659 --> 00:57:07,047
So, Discord, because you can link your accounts, this has been an invaluable tool to verify people, to see if they're real or not.

1058
00:57:07,047 --> 00:57:15,834
And ever since then, we haven't seen any keys on, you know, Kinguin and G2A.

1059
00:57:15,834 --> 00:57:16,815
Speaking of which...

1060
00:57:17,192 --> 00:57:22,815
If your game does end up on Kinguin or G2A without your permission,

1061
00:57:22,815 --> 00:57:27,337
you can send them a message, like an official message,

1062
00:57:27,337 --> 00:57:30,558
say, hey, please take it down and blacklist,

1063
00:57:30,558 --> 00:57:33,800
and then make sure you speak to the manager.

1064
00:57:33,800 --> 00:57:40,683
We did that, and they made sure that they won't show our game on Kinguin or G2A ever again.

1065
00:57:40,683 --> 00:57:43,444
I'm sure this helps some of you guys out there.

1066
00:57:43,444 --> 00:57:45,385
You know what I'm talking about.

1067
00:57:47,800 --> 00:57:52,722
So in your Discord, you also want to have, I mentioned earlier, a feedback and bugs section.

1068
00:57:52,722 --> 00:57:54,743
Just have it, just have them dump it there.

1069
00:57:54,743 --> 00:57:56,925
You can have some bot commands for FAQs,

1070
00:57:56,925 --> 00:58:00,407
like how to get your logs to post it in the bug reports,

1071
00:58:00,407 --> 00:58:02,548
how, uh, FAQ for, like, uh, your links,

1072
00:58:02,548 --> 00:58:05,249
or, you know, anything complex that you say over and over.

1073
00:58:05,249 --> 00:58:06,770
You can have it all bot commands.

1074
00:58:06,770 --> 00:58:10,492
And so, it's sort of like if you ever watched a Twitch streamer,

1075
00:58:10,492 --> 00:58:14,634
you know, you can type ! and a command, and lots of times it'll give them links or information.

1076
00:58:14,634 --> 00:58:16,775
You can do something like that.

1077
00:58:17,598 --> 00:58:22,700
And then news have a read-only section for players to see.

1078
00:58:22,700 --> 00:58:26,322
You can tag everyone, so that even if they're offline,

1079
00:58:26,322 --> 00:58:30,784
they'll eventually see it.

1080
00:58:30,784 --> 00:58:33,425
Let's go to the next slide here.

1081
00:58:33,425 --> 00:58:36,867
So let's talk about Unity.

1082
00:58:36,867 --> 00:58:38,468
Why Unity?

1083
00:58:38,468 --> 00:58:40,789
Well, Unity is free while developing.

1084
00:58:40,789 --> 00:58:43,490
That's always an incentive for indie devs.

1085
00:58:43,490 --> 00:58:45,311
They have an asset store that's invaluable.

1086
00:58:45,905 --> 00:58:50,487
The asset store, I'm sure that you've all experienced it if you've used Unity before.

1087
00:58:50,487 --> 00:58:53,508
They have tons of free assets, or almost free assets.

1088
00:58:53,508 --> 00:58:58,850
Don't forget that your game doesn't have to start with the final assets.

1089
00:58:58,850 --> 00:59:02,532
You saw my blooper video at the very beginning.

1090
00:59:02,532 --> 00:59:07,374
Our game models don't look like that, the textures don't look like that, neither do the shadings.

1091
00:59:07,374 --> 00:59:11,135
But it really allowed us to get started fast.

1092
00:59:11,135 --> 00:59:14,077
To just throw something in there instead of just squares.

1093
00:59:14,551 --> 00:59:21,475
you could have just squares, but it's sort of good for morale, and it's good for screenshots.

1094
00:59:21,475 --> 00:59:26,498
And especially if you're doing a Kickstarter, or you're trying to get some press,

1095
00:59:26,498 --> 00:59:31,462
if you show someone with some type of model, or environment, or art, or some sort of placeholders,

1096
00:59:31,462 --> 00:59:37,005
it's better than just squares, and black and white.

1097
00:59:37,677 --> 00:59:40,618
And that pretty much is the definition of prototyping.

1098
00:59:40,618 --> 00:59:42,238
It's just having a bunch of placeholders

1099
00:59:42,238 --> 00:59:44,858
so that people can envision what your game will

1100
00:59:44,858 --> 00:59:46,419
be when you're finished.

1101
00:59:46,419 --> 00:59:50,199
It doesn't necessarily have to work all the way,

1102
00:59:50,199 --> 00:59:54,320
but give them something to think about.

1103
00:59:54,320 --> 00:59:56,120
Unity is high level.

1104
00:59:56,120 --> 01:00:01,881
This means that unlike Unreal, you

1105
01:00:01,881 --> 01:00:03,862
don't have to program memory management.

1106
01:00:03,862 --> 01:00:07,202
You don't have to program low level physics.

1107
01:00:09,344 --> 01:00:11,266
it'll probably be more efficient if you do.

1108
01:00:11,266 --> 01:00:13,607
I mean, it will be more efficient if you do.

1109
01:00:13,607 --> 01:00:15,729
But the fact that you can

1110
01:00:15,729 --> 01:00:16,690
just skip all this stuff

1111
01:00:16,690 --> 01:00:20,072
and just go straight to making the game

1112
01:00:20,072 --> 01:00:21,854
is really good for morale.

1113
01:00:21,854 --> 01:00:22,875
It's good for prototyping.

1114
01:00:22,875 --> 01:00:23,755
And...

1115
01:00:23,755 --> 01:00:28,159
you can always do the optimization stuff later.

1116
01:00:28,159 --> 01:00:28,819
Right?

1117
01:00:28,819 --> 01:00:31,301
I mean, lots of times when you're making a game,

1118
01:00:31,301 --> 01:00:32,522
you don't want to...

1119
01:00:32,522 --> 01:00:36,425
you want to start with the game itself, not all the lower level stuff.

1120
01:00:36,425 --> 01:00:37,866
You can make games faster.

1121
01:00:37,866 --> 01:00:38,947
It's faster to learn, too.

1122
01:00:39,736 --> 01:00:42,337
and they have good tutorials.

1123
01:00:42,337 --> 01:00:45,699
If you don't know something, just Google it again.

1124
01:00:45,699 --> 01:00:46,279
Watch YouTube video.

1125
01:00:46,279 --> 01:00:49,421
Unity actually has built in, they

1126
01:00:49,421 --> 01:00:52,482
have their own native tutorial videos.

1127
01:00:52,482 --> 01:00:54,143
And they're very high budget tutorials.

1128
01:00:54,143 --> 01:00:55,463
They have videos.

1129
01:00:55,463 --> 01:00:56,404
They have demos.

1130
01:00:56,404 --> 01:01:00,106
They have full games that they can give you to poke around

1131
01:01:00,106 --> 01:01:02,527
with, depending on your learning style.

1132
01:01:02,527 --> 01:01:08,850
Some people like to reverse engineer things.

1133
01:01:09,402 --> 01:01:10,923
You can do multiple ports.

1134
01:01:10,923 --> 01:01:16,825
Nintendo Switch has been really big lately for Indie developers.

1135
01:01:16,825 --> 01:01:19,906
And so you can port it straight to Nintendo Switch

1136
01:01:19,906 --> 01:01:21,126
with almost effortlessly.

1137
01:01:21,126 --> 01:01:24,447
Or at the beginning, we were just going to do Windows.

1138
01:01:24,447 --> 01:01:28,829
And then we realized how easy it was to do Mac and Linux, too.

1139
01:01:28,829 --> 01:01:31,650
So we're just like, OK, all it requires us is to switch to Mac,

1140
01:01:31,650 --> 01:01:34,591
build, done.

1141
01:01:34,591 --> 01:01:37,151
So if you can, you may as well.

1142
01:01:37,988 --> 01:01:41,671
And so, especially if your game is very console-friendly,

1143
01:01:41,671 --> 01:01:44,453
for consoles, you may require some extra stuff,

1144
01:01:44,453 --> 01:01:45,773
like for the controller support.

1145
01:01:45,773 --> 01:01:48,195
You want buttons to go to different buttons.

1146
01:01:48,195 --> 01:01:52,398
But in the long term, it's not that much

1147
01:01:52,398 --> 01:01:59,562
to be able to port it to consoles, too.

1148
01:01:59,562 --> 01:02:00,703
And now, why not Unity?

1149
01:02:00,703 --> 01:02:06,007
So Unity, they don't make games unlike Unreal.

1150
01:02:06,007 --> 01:02:06,987
Unreal.

1151
01:02:07,449 --> 01:02:10,832
makes AAA games that people want to play.

1152
01:02:10,832 --> 01:02:12,573
This means that they're developers too.

1153
01:02:12,573 --> 01:02:16,836
I mean, when I say they, I mean like the big guys,

1154
01:02:16,836 --> 01:02:19,198
the CEOs and stuff.

1155
01:02:19,198 --> 01:02:21,280
And so these guys actually are developers.

1156
01:02:21,280 --> 01:02:24,742
And so if they run into a bug while they're

1157
01:02:24,742 --> 01:02:27,124
making a AAA game, like Unreal Tournament or something,

1158
01:02:27,124 --> 01:02:31,167
then they will go in and they'll fix it.

1159
01:02:31,167 --> 01:02:34,790
But as for Unity, they outsource all their demos.

1160
01:02:34,790 --> 01:02:36,772
And so if they run into a bug.

1161
01:02:37,257 --> 01:02:41,440
then they don't really fix it for a few years.

1162
01:02:41,440 --> 01:02:45,283
And so there are countless unfixed bugs.

1163
01:02:45,283 --> 01:02:49,887
In our examples, in our experience, we have freezes,

1164
01:02:49,887 --> 01:02:52,349
we have crashes, we have UI bugs.

1165
01:02:52,349 --> 01:02:56,252
If you've ever used the scroller in Unity,

1166
01:02:56,252 --> 01:02:59,935
it'll always shift everything over to the side,

1167
01:02:59,935 --> 01:03:02,337
and your screen will sometimes turn pink.

1168
01:03:02,337 --> 01:03:05,920
And it's just not fun.

1169
01:03:07,058 --> 01:03:10,940
But if you experience bugs, because Unity is so modular,

1170
01:03:10,940 --> 01:03:12,201
you can just work around it.

1171
01:03:12,201 --> 01:03:15,002
Go to the Unity store and find an alternative.

1172
01:03:15,002 --> 01:03:17,924
You don't have to use the Unity built-in stuff.

1173
01:03:17,924 --> 01:03:19,585
You don't like the scroller?

1174
01:03:19,585 --> 01:03:22,747
Go in and find a scroller, or you can make your own.

1175
01:03:22,747 --> 01:03:26,949
They make it really easy to be modular in a very simple way.

1176
01:03:26,949 --> 01:03:29,311
I made my own scroller in the end,

1177
01:03:29,311 --> 01:03:32,733
and it ended up not being, it didn't take me very long

1178
01:03:32,733 --> 01:03:35,314
to make, and then I used the template from the Asset Store

1179
01:03:35,314 --> 01:03:36,095
to help me get there.

1180
01:03:37,514 --> 01:03:43,639
So yeah, you will experience bugs, but you can just skip it.

1181
01:03:43,639 --> 01:03:45,921
But be sure that the upgrades are not stable,

1182
01:03:45,921 --> 01:03:48,463
so be sure you copy your entire project,

1183
01:03:48,463 --> 01:03:51,105
and then try upgrading if you're ever trying to upgrade.

1184
01:03:51,105 --> 01:03:53,127
That's the only way to be safe.

1185
01:03:53,127 --> 01:03:57,330
OK, so they're free.

1186
01:03:57,330 --> 01:03:58,311
They're free, actually.

1187
01:03:58,311 --> 01:03:59,792
While you're developing, it's free.

1188
01:03:59,792 --> 01:04:02,114
Even when you launch, it's still free.

1189
01:04:02,114 --> 01:04:03,656
But if you do the personal edition,

1190
01:04:03,656 --> 01:04:05,177
they'll sort of shame you.

1191
01:04:05,177 --> 01:04:07,118
They'll put the personal logo at the bottom.

1192
01:04:07,777 --> 01:04:11,699
So it makes you really unprofessional.

1193
01:04:11,699 --> 01:04:15,820
I've seen people give negative reviews just saying, oh,

1194
01:04:15,820 --> 01:04:19,422
developers are cheap because they have the personal edition

1195
01:04:19,422 --> 01:04:19,842
or something.

1196
01:04:19,842 --> 01:04:24,824
So that's something really to think about, really.

1197
01:04:24,824 --> 01:04:26,745
And so if you make over $100,000 or you

1198
01:04:26,745 --> 01:04:30,306
don't want that personal edition slash screen to show,

1199
01:04:30,306 --> 01:04:32,947
then you can pay for the licenses.

1200
01:04:32,947 --> 01:04:35,528
You don't have to jump to the pro license.

1201
01:04:35,878 --> 01:04:41,283
They have a per seat license, but they have a lower level one that's like $35 per month

1202
01:04:41,283 --> 01:04:47,008
per seat or something like that, if you make under a certain amount of money.

1203
01:04:47,008 --> 01:04:48,289
So it's not bad. It's really not.

1204
01:04:48,289 --> 01:04:58,117
And then lastly, Unity does abandon modules. Think of Unreal more like a game engine and

1205
01:04:58,117 --> 01:05:04,302
Unity more like a sales engine. So lots of times they really push marketing

1206
01:05:04,302 --> 01:05:04,782
very hard.

1207
01:05:05,135 --> 01:05:07,756
so they want to add, they want to get the feature list really high.

1208
01:05:07,756 --> 01:05:12,238
And so that's wonderful, I love features, but not at the cost of stability.

1209
01:05:12,238 --> 01:05:16,960
And, you know, I don't want them, I want them to continuously develop it.

1210
01:05:16,960 --> 01:05:20,782
And in this case, I mentioned U-Net earlier, I said don't use U-Net.

1211
01:05:20,782 --> 01:05:26,004
And then they also have a service called Collab, Collaborate.

1212
01:05:26,004 --> 01:05:28,165
It's very unstable too, it's like Gits.

1213
01:05:28,754 --> 01:05:29,535
Just use Git and GitLab, guys.

1214
01:05:29,535 --> 01:05:31,997
In the end, we got rid of all of our Unity services,

1215
01:05:31,997 --> 01:05:38,143
and suddenly our game editor is way faster and way less buggy.

1216
01:05:38,143 --> 01:05:53,557
So really quickly, what I plan for the future.

1217
01:05:54,786 --> 01:06:01,709
We have a private API, and that API is so that it'll spread out to other services and stuff, like Discord.

1218
01:06:01,709 --> 01:06:07,332
We want a public one, so that people can make community sites without involving us.

1219
01:06:07,332 --> 01:06:11,154
They can have stats sites and stuff, whatever they can come up with.

1220
01:06:11,154 --> 01:06:14,736
We want to improve our UI and UX experience.

1221
01:06:14,736 --> 01:06:22,060
We want to have a better community engagement, so we want to make a Twitch extension, for example, so that players can click.

1222
01:06:22,676 --> 01:06:24,997
And we have different abilities.

1223
01:06:24,997 --> 01:06:27,398
We want them to be able to hover over the abilities

1224
01:06:27,398 --> 01:06:27,999
to see what they do.

1225
01:06:27,999 --> 01:06:29,980
We want them to be able to click on a journal

1226
01:06:29,980 --> 01:06:32,161
and it opens a journal with their last known entry.

1227
01:06:32,161 --> 01:06:35,542
There's some fun stuff you can do with that.

1228
01:06:35,542 --> 01:06:39,404
And because hardly any indie games do this, if you do that,

1229
01:06:39,404 --> 01:06:40,185
you will be on Twitch.

1230
01:06:40,185 --> 01:06:45,267
Because audience engagement is a very rare thing in Twitch.

1231
01:06:45,267 --> 01:06:47,348
And streamers have to work really hard for it.

1232
01:06:47,348 --> 01:06:49,409
So if you can give them something,

1233
01:06:49,409 --> 01:06:51,430
